    "body": "@hesterbruikman \r\n\r\nIf we take again the steps you described:\r\n1/ Cancels the process when asked to write down the PUK code and Pairing code\r\n2/ Generates new keys\r\n3/ Tries to store these Keys on Keycard\r\n\r\nAfter 1/ currently the message the user gets is:\r\n \"Dangerous operation. \r\nThis will cancel keycard setup. It's highly recommended to finish the setup in order to use keycard. Do you really want to cancel ?\"\r\n\r\nAnd the state of his card is that it's initalized with a pairing code + pin + puk, but it has no multiaccount on it. \r\n\r\nWhen the user goes through 2 and 3/ then when he will tap a card, he will not get  the screen you showed, but a request to enter his pairing code. Which he did not write...\r\n\r\nSo for me the issue is really about, not being clear to the user when he cancels the setup in 1/ that if he doesn't write his pairing code, he's actually f***ed and can throw his card away. \r\n\r\nI completed the miro diagram of the onboarding logic (what happens with the card)\r\nhttps://miro.com/app/board/o9J_kvIXxoU=/\r\n\r\nPossible solutions I see: \r\ni/ change the warning to something much more explicit\r\nii/ change where the actual pairing of the card is done with the phone + allow a user to change his pairing code when he knows his PIN. So if the user cancels here, then he can resume (only with the same phone), and then he can set up a new pairing code in the settings\r\n\r\nI prefer i/ since ii/ needs to build this new 'change pairing code' feature which will be longer\r\n\r\n\r\n",
